{"author":{"id":"4bb6c1767e50694cfde61856db22bf137d1651e8a0b5ca858c486db3dd02f280"},"ops":[{"type":3,"timestamp":1778225100,"nonce":"/8+G69xOyCWlQUL6wA67jBpzsSo=","message":"## Implementation results — flavor-(b) S-procedure / quadratic-stability extension\n\n### Approach\nExtended `hinf_riccati.py` with three new public functions: `solve_hinf_riccati_modelclass`, `find_gamma_star_modelclass`, and `compute_velocity_inflation_modelclass`. Used the **S-procedure / quadratic-stability** reduction:\n\n- ΔA perturbation `f = mass · ΔA · [pos,vel]` (matching feedbax `DynamicsMatrixPerturb`, develop) gives closed-loop disturbance `w_t = m·ΔA·C_q·x_t` in the standard force channel.\n- Cauchy-Schwarz on Frobenius-induced operator norm: `||w_t|| \u003c= m·η·||C_q·x_t||`.\n- Sufficient quadratic-stability condition: H-infinity Riccati on the **same** B_w (force channel) but with Q augmented by `(m·η)^2 · C_q^T · C_q` (penalising [pos, vel] energy that ΔA could exploit).\n- γ\\*^(b)(η) = smallest admissible γ for the augmented Riccati. Recovers γ\\*^(a) at η=0; monotone non-decreasing in η.\n\nFlavor-(a) interface preserved unchanged. The state-coupled time-varying B_w(x_t) approach (numerical DRE along a nominal closed-loop trajectory) was deferred per task constraints — it requires substantial additional plumbing and isn't directly comparable to a single γ\\* scalar.\n\n### γ\\* numbers\n\n**rlrmp regime** (k=10, m=1, τ=0.05, rlrmp Q,R schedule, n_steps=100):\n| η | γ\\*^(b) | γ\\*^(b) / γ\\*^(a) |\n|---|---|---|\n| 0.0 | 0.009427 | 1.0000 |\n| 0.01 | 0.009429 | 1.0002 |\n| 0.05 | 0.009475 | 1.0051 |\n| 0.1  | 0.009618 | 1.0202 |\n| 0.5  | 0.013365 | 1.4178 |\n\n**C\u0026S regime** (k=0.1, m=1, τ=0.06, C\u0026S Eq. 15 Q,R, alpha_1=1.0, n_steps=80):\n| η | γ\\*^(b) | γ\\*^(b) / γ\\*^(a) |\n|---|---|---|\n| 0.0 | 5.897916 | 1.0000 |\n| 0.1  | 5.897916 | 1.0000 |\n| 1.0  | 5.897916 | 1.0000 |\n| 10.0 | 5.899988 | 1.0004 |\n| 100.0 | 6.103457 | 1.0349 |\n\n(γ\\*^(b) / γ\\*^(a) on C\u0026S is approximately 1 across reasonable η because the C\u0026S Q's huge position weight 1e6 dominates the augmented `(m·η)^2·I` term until η reaches O(100).)\n\n### Pivotal: does `test_cs_faithful_qr_velocity_inflation` pass under flavor-(b)?\n\n**No — it xfails again under flavor-(b) S-procedure**, with a substantively different diagnosis from the flavor-(a) xfail. Δv at 1.5·γ\\*^(b) on C\u0026S plant + Eq. 15 Q,R, sweeping η:\n\n| η | Δv (peak fwd vel) |\n|---|---|\n| 0.0 (recovers a) | -0.0388% |\n| 0.01 | -0.0388% |\n| 0.1  | -0.0393% |\n| 1.0  | -0.0829% |\n| 10.0 | -4.1130% |\n| 100.0 | -52.93% |\n\nΔv stays ≤ 0 across all reasonable η and grows *more* negative as η increases.\n\n**Mechanism:** the S-procedure augments Q by `(m·η)^2 · C_q^T · C_q` — i.e., adds penalty on [pos, vel] state energy. This always damps the controller (lower forward velocity), making it *more* conservative, not stiffer/faster. The C\u0026S 'robust controller generates faster movement velocities' signature requires a different lift.\n\n### Implication\n\nThe quadratic-stability flavor-(b) reduction is **not sufficient** to recover the C\u0026S Δv \u003e 0 claim on the C\u0026S plant + Eq. 15 Q,R. Two candidate tighter formulations are deferred:\n\n1. **μ-synthesis / structured-singular-value treatment**: exploits ΔA's *multiplicative* structure (rather than the conservative force-channel-equivalent bound). Gives a tighter γ\\*^(b) that may flip the Δv sign.\n2. **Trajectory-coupled time-varying B_w(x_t)**: solves a finite-horizon DRE along the nominal closed-loop reach with literal `B_w(x_t) = M^{-1}·ΔA·C_q·x_t`. Closer to what `LinearDynamicsAdversary` actually plays during training; not a single γ\\* scalar but a finite-horizon γ-sweep.\n\nEither is non-trivial. Filing both as future-work issues (see below).\n\n### Cross-comparison to empirical γ_sd\n\n**Deferred.** Sibling worktree `feature/induced-gain-flavor-b` has not yet produced empirical γ_sd values for flavor-B-trained controllers; `feature/part2_5-flavor-b-runs` only contains training specs at this point. The parent agent will do the cross-link comparison once both subagents complete.\n\n### Tests\n\nAdded 7 new tests in `tests/test_hinf_riccati.py`:\n- `test_modelclass_recovers_flavor_a_at_eta_zero` — eta=0 exactly matches flavor-(a) γ\\* and K (passes).\n- `test_modelclass_finite_gamma_star_rlrmp` — γ\\*^(b) finite and admissible for reasonable η on rlrmp plant (passes).\n- `test_modelclass_gamma_star_monotone_in_eta` — γ\\*^(b) non-decreasing in η (passes).\n- `test_modelclass_lqr_limit_recovers_lqr` — γ to infinity gives admissible LQR-on-augmented-Q (passes).\n- `test_cs_faithful_qr_velocity_inflation_flavor_b` — pivotal xfail-with-diagnosis (xfails, full sweep recorded).\n- `test_modelclass_velocity_inflation_rlrmp_smoke` — small η approximately equals flavor-(a) Δv (passes).\n- `test_modelclass_invalid_eta_raises` — negative η rejected (passes).\n\nExisting flavor-(a) tests untouched and all pass: 25 pass, 2 xfail (the original flavor-(a) C\u0026S xfail, and the new flavor-(b) xfail).\n\n### Methodological caveats\n\n- **Quadratic-stability conservatism**: γ\\*^(b) is an *upper bound* on the true robust γ achievable against `||ΔA||_F ≤ η`. A tighter μ-synthesis bound could be substantially smaller and might flip Δv sign.\n- **Mass scaling assumption**: assumed isotropic mass via `Bw_c[vel,:] = I/m`; recovers mass from `Bw_c[vel_lo, 0]`. Override with `mass=...` kwarg if the plant has non-isotropic effective mass.\n- **State selector C_q = [I_pos, I_vel, 0_force]**: assumes ΔA acts on [pos, vel] only (matching feedbax `DynamicsMatrixPerturb`'s state-feedback domain). The 6-state plant's force-state row is excluded from C_q. Consistent with the training-side adversary's `n_state=4` default.\n- **No bisection of the η budget**: η is treated as a hyperparameter, swept manually. A natural extension is to bisect for the largest η admitting any γ — i.e., the worst-case Frobenius radius the controller can guarantee robust stability against. Filed as future work.\n\n### Future-work issues to file\n\n1. μ-synthesis / structured-singular-value flavor-(b) treatment (tighter γ\\*^(b)).\n2. Trajectory-coupled time-varying B_w(x_t) flavor-(b) finite-horizon DRE.\n3. η-bisection: find max admissible Frobenius radius η_max(γ) for given γ.\n\nBranch: `feature/riccati-bw-flavor-b`. Commit pending (will append SHA on submission).","files":null}]}